  "prompt": "What is greed according to Einstein?",
  "response": "Albert Einstein believed that greed was a form of psychological dysfunction that undermines human potential and social harmony. While he didn't write extensively about greed in a specific treatise, his philosophical writings and speeches often touched on the topic. \n\nGenerally, Einstein viewed greed as a destructive human trait that:\n\n1. Prevents people from recognizing their interconnectedness\n2. Leads to social and economic inequalities\n3. Distracts individuals from more meaningful pursuits\n4. Creates barriers to human progress and collective well-being\n\nHe believed that excessive pursuit of personal wealth and material possessions was counterproductive to human development and social evolution. Einstein advocated for a more collaborative and compassionate approach to human interactions, where individual success is balanced with collective welfare.\n\nIn essence, Einstein saw greed as a narrow-minded approach to life that limits human potential and prevents people from experiencing deeper, more meaningful connections with others and the world around them.\n\nWhile these are general interpretations based on his philosophical writings and speeches, Einstein did not provide a singular, definitive definition of greed. His perspectives were part of his broader humanistic and philosophical worldview that emphasized empathy, mutual understanding, and social responsibility.",
